    <para styleclass="Normal" style="margin-top:10px; margin-left:10px; line-height:1.0; tabstops:none;"><text styleclass="Normal" style="font-size:11pt; text-decoration:none; vertical-align:baseline;" translate="true">&#32;</text></para>
    <para styleclass="Normal" style="margin-top:10px; margin-left:10px; line-height:1.0; tabstops:none;"><text styleclass="Normal" style="font-size:11pt; text-decoration:none; vertical-align:baseline;" translate="true">The </text><text styleclass="Normal" style="font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:none; vertical-align:baseline;" translate="true">ClearCanvas Web Viewer</text><text styleclass="Normal" style="font-size:11pt; text-decoration:none; vertical-align:baseline;" translate="true"> is a simple web-based medical image viewer that leverages existing functionality from </text><text styleclass="Normal" style="font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:none; vertical-align:baseline;" translate="true">ClearCanvas Image Viewer</text><text styleclass="Normal" style="font-size:11pt; text-decoration:none; vertical-align:baseline;" translate="true">. &#160;In fact, for the functionality that has been included in the Web Viewer, users should notice very little difference between the two. &#160;Web viewer technology is not new; there are many of them out there, but few meet the demands of users, especially in a clinical setting, and most are just toys. &#160;The architecture of the ClearCanvas Web Viewer is simple and flexible, and because it actually </text><text styleclass="Normal" style="font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; font-style:italic; text-decoration:none; vertical-align:baseline;" translate="true">uses</text><text styleclass="Normal" style="font-size:11pt; text-decoration:none; vertical-align:baseline;" translate="true"> the Image Viewer under the hood, it is capable of expanding it&apos;s feature set in tandem with the Image Viewer. &#160;Not only that, but it integrates seamlessly into any other web-based, or web-capable application.</text></para>
    <para styleclass="Normal" style="margin-top:10px; margin-left:10px; line-height:1.0; tabstops:none;"><text styleclass="Normal" style="font-size:11pt; text-decoration:none; vertical-align:baseline;" translate="true">The diagram below shows the </text><text styleclass="Normal" style="font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:none; vertical-align:baseline;" translate="true">Web Viewer</text><text styleclass="Normal" style="font-size:11pt; text-decoration:none; vertical-align:baseline;" translate="true"> in the larger context of the </text><text styleclass="Normal" style="font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:none; vertical-align:baseline;" translate="true">ClearCanvas RIS/PACS</text><text styleclass="Normal" style="font-size:11pt; text-decoration:none; vertical-align:baseline;" translate="true">.</text></para>
    <para styleclass="Normal" style="margin-top:10px; margin-left:106px; line-height:1.0; tabstops:none;"><image src="ccrispacs-webviewer.png" scale="100.00%" styleclass="Image Caption"></image></para>
    <para styleclass="Normal" style="margin-top:10px; margin-bottom:10px; margin-left:10px; line-height:1.0; tabstops:none;"><text styleclass="Normal" style="font-size:11pt; text-decoration:none; vertical-align:baseline;" translate="true">As you can see from the diagram, the Web Viewer is currently considered part of the ImageServer product, and indeed it is, because you can launch the Web Viewer from the ImageServer&apos;s web UI. &#160;However, though the Web Viewer does currently have a direct dependency on ImageServer, eventually we hope to make it work with other archives. &#160;Also, the Web Viewer actually encompasses the Image Viewer as part of it&apos;s service layer, blurring the lines between the Viewer (or Workstation) and ImageServer products.</text></para>
